    {
      "key": "step_1_concept_analysis",
      "type": "string",
      "required": true,
      "description": "Explain the System Mechanism and ISAC Coupling Mode found.",
      "value": "The system mechanism involves the use of visible light communication (VLC) for integrated sensing and communication (ISAC) in a vehicle-to-vehicle (V2V) scenario. The ISAC coupling mode is divided into two parts: the target channel and the background channel. The target channel models the interaction of a deterministic target on the received signal, while the background channel models the interaction of the environment other than the target on the received signal."
    },
    {
      "key": "step_2_benchmark_verification",
      "type": "string",
      "required": true,
      "description": "Validate the physical consistency of reported metrics (Rate/Resolution).",
      "value": "The paper reports on the simulation results of the channel characteristics, including the path loss, root mean square (RMS) delay spread, and received power ratio of the target channel and background channel for mono-static sensing and bi-static sensing. The results show that the received power of the target channel of mono-static sensing fades faster than that of bi-static sensing with distance increases, and the RMS DS of mono-static sensing is larger than that of bi-static sensing."
    },
    {
      "key": "step_3_strategic_critique",
      "type": "string",
      "required": true,
      "description": "Identify the solved problems and remaining open challenges.",
      "value": "The paper solves the problem of characterizing the visible light-based ISAC channel in a V2V scenario, providing insights into the channel characteristics and performance of mono-static sensing and bi-static sensing. However, the paper also highlights the need for further research on the sensing channel, especially in outdoor environments, and the importance of considering key factors such as large-scale fading, Doppler effects, and multipath effects in the characterization of ISAC channels."
    }
